<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-27T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-27T23:00:00-05:00" n="96" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3665: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="from">Cunningham</persName>) to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-28T12:00:00+08:00">January 28,
                                1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 28—3 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Defense Committee this morning decided to ask the Municipal Council
                            to declare from 4 o’clock this afternoon a state of emergency. <pb facs="0187" n="83" xml:id="pg_83"/> The Council convenes at 12
                            o’clock and will undoubtedly declare a state of emergency.</p>
                        <p>2. The Japanese flagship was anchored last night in front of the Japanese
                            Consulate. At 8:30 this morning a bomb was thrown presumably intended
                            for the Japanese Consul General exploding at the corner of the Japanese
                            consular property where the prison is located.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to the Legation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_CES1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>